Making a new repo
log in to GitHub.com and create a new, empty repository (name it kimballH). 
Do not initialize it with a README, license, or gitignore if you want to keep the process simple.
Initialize and Push Your Folder
Open your terminal and run these commands to connect your local folder to GitHub
.1.Navigate to your folder:Terminal.Change directory into your kimballH folder:
	Bash cd /path/to/your/kimballH
2.Initialize Git:Setup.Turn the folder into a Git repository:
	Bash git init -b main
3.Add files to staging:Tracking.Stage all files in the folder to be committed:
	Bash git add .
4.Commit changes:Snapshot.Create your initial commit:
	Bash git commit -m "Initial commit of KimballH photos and data"
5.Connect to GitHub:Remote.Add the remote URL 
	(replace YOUR_USERNAME with your GitHub handle):
	Bash git remote add origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/kimballH.git
6.Push to GitHub:Sync.Upload your files to the main branch:
	Bash git push -u origin main

Important: Large File Handling (Git LFS)Since you are working with photos (HEIF/JPEG), do not upload them to GitHub if the folder is large (over 100MB total). GitHub will reject files larger than 100MB and will struggle with large image libraries.If you intend to store these photos in this repository, you must use Git LFS (Large File Storage):
	Install LFS: git lfs install
	Track images: Run this inside the kimballH folder:
	Bash 	git lfs track "*.jpg" "*.heic" "*.heif" "*.tif"
		git add .gitattributes

Continue with the git add . and git commit steps above.


Updating a github

To update your live website, you must "stage," "commit," and "push" your changes from your terminal. Git treats these as three distinct steps to ensure you have a record of what you changed.

Run these three commands in your terminal, ensuring you are inside the Kimball folder:

The Update Sequence
Bash
# 1. Stage the file (tells Git you want to include this specific file in the update)
git add index.html

# 2. Commit the change (saves the change to your local history with a description)
git commit -m "Fix ISO metadata display in index.html"

# 3. Push to GitHub (uploads your local changes to the remote repository)
git push origin main


What happens next?GitHub Receives the Data: Once you run git push, your code on GitHub.com will immediately reflect the corrected file.

Automatic Rebuild: GitHub Pages detects the new commit automatically. It will trigger a "rebuild" process that takes roughly 30–60 seconds.

Live Update: Your site at [https://imagehub.github.io/Kimball/](https://imagehub.github.io/Kimball/) will update to show the new data automatically.

If you don’t see the change immediately, perform a hard refresh in your browser (Ctrl + F5 on Windows/Linux or Cmd + Shift + R on Mac) to clear the cached version of the old file.

Note: If you also updated gallery-data.json, make sure to run git add gallery-data.json before the commit command as well.


Activating the website


PrerequisitesFor GitHub Pages to work, your website files (HTML, CSS, JS) must be in the repository.If you have an index.html file: It should be in the root folder of your kimballH repository.If you don't have these files: You will need to create them before the site will display anything.


How to Enable GitHub Pages Follow these steps to turn your repository into a live website:
1.Open GitHub Settings:Browser.Go to GitHub.com, navigate to your kimballH repository, and click the Settings tab at the top.

2.Navigate to Pages:Sidebar.In the left-hand sidebar, click on the Pages menu item.

3.Configure Source:Build and deployment.Under the Build and deployment section, ensure the "Source" dropdown is set to Deploy from a branch.

4.Select Branch:Branch dropdown.Under "Branch," select main (or master) from the dropdown and ensure the folder is set to /(root). Click Save.Access Your Live SiteAfter clicking Save, GitHub will automatically build your site.Wait 1–2 minutes: GitHub needs a moment to process the files.Check Status: Refresh the Pages settings page. You will see a banner at the top that says: "Your site is live at..." followed by a URL.Visit: Click that link to view your published website.Important Note for Image GalleriesSince you mentioned your repository contains a large library of photos (.heic, .jpg) and a gallery-data.json file:Performance: Browsers cannot display HEIC/HEIF files natively. If your website code relies on these raw files, they will likely show as broken images. Ensure your website script converts these to WebP or JPEG for web compatibility.Data Fetching: Ensure your gallery-data.json file is in the root directory so your index.html can fetch it using a relative path like fetch('./gallery-data.json').
